# Incubyte TDD Discipline

This is the **primary rule** of the workspace. The Incubyte assessment is graded on the visible TDD evolution in `git log`. Violating this rule is the single fastest way to fail the assessment.

## The Three Laws of TDD (Uncle Bob)

1. **You are not allowed to write any production code unless it is to make a failing unit test pass.**
2. **You are not allowed to write any more of a unit test than is sufficient to fail; and compilation failures are failures.**
3. **You are not allowed to write any more production code than is sufficient to pass the one currently failing unit test.**

These laws are non-negotiable. They force a tight RED → GREEN → REFACTOR loop of seconds-to-minutes per cycle.

## The loop, every time

For every behavior change (feature, bug fix, refactor target):

1. **RED** — Write the smallest possible failing test that describes the next behavior. Run it. **Confirm it fails** and paste the failure message. If you cannot make a test fail, you do not understand the behavior yet.
2. **Commit** with `test: <behavior>` (the test alone, failing).
3. **GREEN** — Write the **minimum** production code that makes the test pass. No more. No "I'll need this later." No premature abstraction. Run the test. Confirm it passes.
4. **Commit** with `feat: <behavior>` (or `fix:` for regression tests).
5. **REFACTOR** — Improve the code AND/OR the test without changing behavior. Re-run **all** tests. If anything breaks, undo and try a smaller refactor.
6. **Commit** with `refactor: <what improved, why>` if you changed anything.
7. Loop back to step 1 for the next behavior.

The full one-screen recipe lives at `.cursor/skills/incubyte-tdd-loop/SKILL.md`.

## What counts as a test (preference order)

| Level | Cost | Coverage focus |
|-------|------|----------------|
| **Unit** | Cheap, fast (<10ms) | Most behavior. Default level. |
| **Integration** | Medium | Route ↔ service ↔ DB wiring; SQL queries. |
| **E2E / API** | Expensive, slower | Critical happy paths only. |
| **UI snapshot** | Avoid | Brittle. Use behavioral component tests (Vitest + RTL) instead. |

Default to unit tests. Reach for integration only when the unit cannot exercise the wiring under review.

## TDD anti-patterns (don't do these)

- **Writing tests after the code.** This is not TDD. The test will only describe what was built, not what should have been built.
- **Skipping the RED step.** "It would fail anyway" is not evidence. Run it and see the failure.
- **Implementing two behaviors in one GREEN step.** One test, one behavior, one commit.
- **Mocking everything.** Mock at the system boundary (HTTP, filesystem, time). Do not mock your own service or repository unless the test is genuinely about coordination.
- **Refactoring on red.** If any test is failing, you may only either (a) revert or (b) write the smallest code to get back to green. No structural changes.
- **Commenting out a failing test to keep the suite green.** Either fix it, fix the production code, or delete the test with an explanatory commit.
- **Tests that test the implementation.** Test observable behavior. If you must reach into internals, the design is probably wrong.

## Refactoring untested code

Per Sandro Mancuso: **you cannot change untested production code safely**. If you must refactor a module that lacks tests:

1. Write a **characterization test** that captures the current behavior (even if it is wrong). Commit it.
2. Refactor with the characterization test as your safety net.
3. Once the refactor is done and green, fix any wrong behavior the characterization test pinned down — each as its own RED → GREEN cycle.

## What "done" means

A change is done when:

- [ ] The new behavior has at least one passing test that fails without the production change.
- [ ] All tests in the suite pass.
- [ ] `git log --oneline` for this change shows a `test:` commit preceding the `feat:`/`fix:` commit.
- [ ] No commit bundles a test, an implementation, and a refactor together.
- [ ] No production code exists that is not exercised by at least one test (coverage ≥ 90% on changed modules; see `incubyte-testing.mdc`).

